Unlocking Insights: Exploratory Data Analysis of Vehicle Insurance Trends
¶

¶

Problem Statement:¶

The increasing complexity of vehicle insurance management, including identifying risk factors, understanding customer demographics, and optimizing policyholder retention, poses challenges for insurance providers. Effective data analysis is critical to uncover patterns and insights that can drive strategic decisions, such as tailoring policies and improving customer satisfaction.

Goal:¶

To conduct an exploratory data analysis (EDA) on the vehicle insurance dataset to identify key trends, relationships, and insights that can assist in understanding policyholder behavior, risk profiling, and optimizing insurance offerings.

Dataset Description¶

This dataset contains information about policyholders and their insurance details. Below is a brief description of the key variables:

Key Variables

  1. id - A unique identifier for each record.
  2. Gender- The gender of the policyholder.
    • "Male"
    • "Female"
  3. Age- The age of the policyholder (numerical value).
  4. Driving_License- A binary indicator to signify whether the policyholder has a driving license.
    • 1: Has a driving license
    • 0: Does not have a driving license
  5. Region_Code- A code representing the geographic region of the policyholder (numerical value).
  6. Previously_Insured- A binary indicator to signify if the policyholder had a previous insurance policy.
    • "Yes"
    • "No"
  7. Vehicle_Age- The age of the vehicle (numerical value, in years).
  8. Vehicle_Damage- A binary indicator to signify if the vehicle has been previously damaged.
    • "Yes"
    • "No"
  9. Annual_Premium- The annual premium amount for the insurance policy (numerical value).
  10. Policy_Sales_Channel- The channel through which the policy was sold (numerical code representing the sales channel).
  11. Vintage- The duration (in days) for which the policyholder has been with the insurance company (numerical value).
  12. Response- A binary target variable indicating whether the policyholder renewed the policy. - 1: Policy was renewed - 0: Policy was not renewed

# List of specific columns to plot
columns_to_plot = ['Age', 'Region_Code', 'Annual_Premium','Policy_Sales_Channel','Vintage']

# Plot box plots for the selected columns
plt.figure(figsize=(5, len(columns_to_plot) * 3))  # Adjust figure size
for i, column in enumerate(columns_to_plot):
    plt.subplot(len(columns_to_plot), 1, i + 1)
    sns.boxplot(x=df[column])
    plt.title(f'Box Plot of {column} before treating Outliers')
    plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Findings and Insights¶

  • The Annual Premium column in the dataset contains numerous outliers. These outliers can skew the results and lead to inaccurate predictions in any models built using this data. Therefore, it is essential to address and treat these outliers to ensure the integrity and reliability of any subsequent analysis.

  • On the other hand, the remaining columns exhibit minimal or no outliers and can be considered stable. Consequently, the primary focus should be on handling the outliers in the Annual Premium column.

Replacing outliers by lower bound and by upper bound¶

In [6]:
def replace_outliers(data, column):
    Q1 = data[column].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = data[column].quantile(0.75)
    
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    
    # Replace values below lower bound with lower bound and values above upper bound with upper bound
    data[column] = data[column].apply(lambda x: lower_bound if x < lower_bound else (upper_bound if x > upper_bound else x))
    
    return data

data = replace_outliers(df2, 'Annual_Premium')

sales_channel_frequency = df2.groupby('Policy_Sales_Channel')['Response'].mean()
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.bar(sales_channel_frequency.index, sales_channel_frequency.values, color="lightcoral")
plt.title('Claim Frequency by Policy Sales Channel')
plt.xlabel('Policy Sales Channel')
plt.ylabel('Claim Frequency (Proportion)')
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.show()

Insights¶

Policy Analysis:¶
  • Most policy sales channels have relatively low claim frequencies, generally below 0.2.
  • A few specific sales channels (notably around 40 and 120) exhibit extremely high claim frequencies, reaching 1.0, indicating that all policies sold through these channels resulted in claims.
  • There is significant variability in claim frequencies across the sales channels, with some clusters showing moderate frequencies and others near-zero.
  • This suggests that certain sales channels are highly associated with claims, likely requiring further investigation into their policyholder demographics or practices.

Recommendations¶

  • Customer Engagement & Segmentation: Target male customers with specific marketing campaigns and design tailored offers for different vehicle age groups to enhance engagement and retention.
  • Address Vehicle Damage & Uninsured Trends: Develop specialized insurance plans for vehicles with damage, preventive maintenance programs for those without, and attract previously uninsured individuals with introductory offers.
  • Personalization & Technology Enhancement: Use data analytics and AI for personalized interactions, decision-making, and strengthen digital presence to improve customer support and access to services.

Insights¶

  • Policy_Sales_Channel and Age have a moderate negative correlation (-0.578) —older customers might prefer specific channels less.
  • Most features show weak or negligible correlation with Response.

Recommendations¶

  • Focus on Non-Insured Customers: Target individuals without prior insurance, as they are more likely to convert. Adjust marketing efforts accordingly.
  • Optimize Sales Channels for Older Customers: Revise strategies for older customer groups, potentially leveraging channels better suited to their preferences.

Recommendations¶

  • Streamlined claims: Consider faster processing for damaged vehicle claims to improve efficiency.

Recommendations:¶

  • For non-insured customers: Target them with insurance benefits campaigns and analyze the claim-prone segment (12.2%) for tailored products.

Insights:¶

  • Stable claim patterns over time: The frequency of claims remains relatively consistent across the "vintage" period (0–300 days), with only minor fluctuations.

Recommendations:¶

  • Engagement strategies: Introduce initiatives to encourage more claim responses over time, possibly through customer engagement or outreach.
  • Monitor early claims: There is a slight increase in claims around the early stages (first 50 days). Investigate why customers are more likely to claim during this period for potential improvements.
